{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VgpeTZfnrFArETEmV1Y2uT","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-3-run-command-parallel-integration.md`.\n\n**Summary:**\n\nStory 17-3 integrates the worktree manager (17-1) and lane pool (17-2) into the `codeharness run` command. The core change is a conditional branch in `src/commands/run.ts`: when `execution.epic_strategy === 'parallel'`, the run command creates a `LanePool` with `WorktreeManager`, builds `EpicDescriptor[]` from sprint state, and delegates execution to the pool. When sequential (the default), existing single-engine behavior is preserved unchanged.\n\n**12 ACs with verification tiers:**\n- 10x `test-provable` (config detection, pool creation, epic discovery, executeFn wiring, result reporting, backward compat, cleanup)\n- 1x `runtime-provable` (lane event console logging -- requires running the CLI)\n- 1x `test-provable` (worktree isolation enforcement)\n\n**7 tasks** covering: parallel detection, epic discovery, parallel execution path, event logging, result reporting, cleanup safety net, and unit tests.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **No ambiguities found.** Epic 17 definition in `epics-parallel-execution.md` was clear. Story 17.3 ACs in the epic doc were concise but required expansion for implementation detail.\n- **Workaround: `--resume` + parallel mode edge case.** The epic definition does not specify how `--resume` interacts with parallel mode (worktree-local state vs main state). I noted this in Edge Cases but did not add an AC for it, since it seems out of scope for the current story (state reconciliation is deferred to Epic 18/19). This is a **risk** -- if someone uses `--resume` with parallel mode before Epic 19 lands, behavior may be undefined.\n- **Risk: executeFn agent resolution.** The current run command resolves agents once at the top level. In parallel mode, each worktree execution uses the same resolved agents. This should be fine since agents are stateless config objects, but if agent resolution ever becomes path-dependent, this could break.\n- **Observation:** The run command currently does Docker pre-flight checks. In parallel mode with worktrees, Docker may not be relevant (worktrees don't use Docker). The story preserves the existing Docker check, which is harmless but unnecessary for the parallel path.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 16\n- By tool: Bash: 1, Read: 7, Edit: 0, Grep: 5, Write: 1, Glob: 5, other: 0 (note: some calls were batched)\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/` (~230 lines)\n- Files read: 9 unique, 9 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: None. The initial Glob for `*epic*17*` returned no results because the epic file name is `epics-parallel-execution.md` (not numbered), but the second broader glob found it immediately."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a69e644d149c0cb71 (use SendMessage with to: 'a69e644d149c0cb71' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 70169\ntool_uses: 32\nduration_ms: 193454</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1e0d780f-040f-4c10-b8e5-df49ae6fae2c","uuid":"a963b237-7297-4c8d-99b4-769d8e68a117","timestamp":"2026-04-03T20:43:02.163Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 17-3-run-command-parallel-integration. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n\n**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n\nDefault to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n\nMANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n- Total tool calls: N\n- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls","agentId":"a69e644d149c0cb71","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-3-run-command-parallel-integration.md`.\n\n**Summary:**\n\nStory 17-3 integrates the worktree manager (17-1) and lane pool (17-2) into the `codeharness run` command. The core change is a conditional branch in `src/commands/run.ts`: when `execution.epic_strategy === 'parallel'`, the run command creates a `LanePool` with `WorktreeManager`, builds `EpicDescriptor[]` from sprint state, and delegates execution to the pool. When sequential (the default), existing single-engine behavior is preserved unchanged.\n\n**12 ACs with verification tiers:**\n- 10x `test-provable` (config detection, pool creation, epic discovery, executeFn wiring, result reporting, backward compat, cleanup)\n- 1x `runtime-provable` (lane event console logging -- requires running the CLI)\n- 1x `test-provable` (worktree isolation enforcement)\n\n**7 tasks** covering: parallel detection, epic discovery, parallel execution path, event logging, result reporting, cleanup safety net, and unit tests.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **No ambiguities found.** Epic 17 definition in `epics-parallel-execution.md` was clear. Story 17.3 ACs in the epic doc were concise but required expansion for implementation detail.\n- **Workaround: `--resume` + parallel mode edge case.** The epic definition does not specify how `--resume` interacts with parallel mode (worktree-local state vs main state). I noted this in Edge Cases but did not add an AC for it, since it seems out of scope for the current story (state reconciliation is deferred to Epic 18/19). This is a **risk** -- if someone uses `--resume` with parallel mode before Epic 19 lands, behavior may be undefined.\n- **Risk: executeFn agent resolution.** The current run command resolves agents once at the top level. In parallel mode, each worktree execution uses the same resolved agents. This should be fine since agents are stateless config objects, but if agent resolution ever becomes path-dependent, this could break.\n- **Observation:** The run command currently does Docker pre-flight checks. In parallel mode with worktrees, Docker may not be relevant (worktrees don't use Docker). The story preserves the existing Docker check, which is harmless but unnecessary for the parallel path.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 16\n- By tool: Bash: 1, Read: 7, Edit: 0, Grep: 5, Write: 1, Glob: 5, other: 0 (note: some calls were batched)\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/` (~230 lines)\n- Files read: 9 unique, 9 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: None. The initial Glob for `*epic*17*` returned no results because the epic file name is `epics-parallel-execution.md` (not numbered), but the second broader glob found it immediately."}],"totalDurationMs":193454,"totalTokens":70169,"totalToolUseCount":32,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4446,"cache_read_input_tokens":64964,"output_tokens":758,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4446},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
