{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KrDuJXvL9iMGiH4fKqNTEw","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n## Code Review Summary\n\n**Story:** 17-3-run-command-parallel-integration\n**Issues Found:** 2 High, 3 Medium, 2 Low\n\n### Issues Fixed (HIGH + MEDIUM)\n\n1. **HIGH — 20+ TypeScript compilation errors in test file** (`src/commands/__tests__/run-parallel.test.ts`). The `@ts-expect-error` directives were unnecessary (variables are accessible within the hoisted closure). Mock function signatures didn't accept parameters, causing spread-argument type errors. The `getSprintStateMock` return type was inferred too narrowly from the initial `Fail` return, preventing test overrides with `Ok<SprintState>`. The no-execution-config test was missing required fields. All fixed by: removing unused directives, adding parameter annotations to mock factory functions, adding explicit return type to `getSprintStateMock`, fixing mock wrapper patterns in `vi.mock()` calls, and adding proper fields to the no-execution test.\n\n2. **HIGH — Mock wrappers used `args as []` cast** that passed zero args to functions needing them. Fixed by passing individual `args[N]` values to each mock.\n\n3. **MEDIUM — `poolInstance.onEvent` typed as `unknown`** due to `Record<string, unknown>` typing. Fixed by casting to `ReturnType<typeof vi.fn>` before accessing `.mock.calls`.\n\n4. **MEDIUM — No-execution-config test missing `storyFlow`/`epicFlow` fields.** TypeScript inference from the initial mock return type required all fields present. Fixed by adding the fields with `execution: undefined`.\n\n5. **MEDIUM — Mock return type for `resolveWorkflowMock`** was too strict — `execution` was required. Fixed by adding explicit return type annotation with `execution?` optional.\n\n### Coverage Results\n\n- Overall: 96.7% (target: 90%) -- PASS\n- Per-file floor: all 178 files above 80% -- PASS\n- Test count: 180 test files, all passing (61 tests in run.test.ts + run-parallel.test.ts combined)\n\n### Files Modified\n\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/commands/__tests__/run-parallel.test.ts` — Fixed all TypeScript compilation errors\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-3-run-command-parallel-integration.md` — Status updated to `verifying`\n\n---\n\n## Session Issues\n\n### Bugs found and severity\n- **HIGH**: 20+ TypeScript compilation errors in `run-parallel.test.ts` — mock types were wrong, @ts-expect-error directives were stale, spread argument patterns were invalid. All fixed.\n- **HIGH**: Mock wrapper functions in `vi.mock()` used `...(args as [])` cast that silently dropped all arguments. Fixed.\n- **MEDIUM**: `poolInstance.onEvent` accessed as `unknown` type — accessing `.mock.calls` on it was a type error. Fixed.\n\n### Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority, tech debt)\n- **LOW**: `executeFn` in `run.ts` (line 271) ignores the `epicId` parameter (`_epicId`). The engine config doesn't scope execution to a specific epic's stories — each worktree engine will process all stories in the workflow, not just the epic's stories. This is likely intentional per story scope (deferred to Epic 18/19), but it means parallel mode currently runs the full workflow in each worktree, which is redundant.\n- **LOW**: `countStories` is both imported (line 8) and re-exported (line 26) from `run.ts`. The re-export is for backward compatibility with existing tests that import from `run.js`, but the dual pattern is fragile.\n\n### Coverage gaps\n- No integration test for the interaction between `run.ts` parallel path and real `LanePool`/`WorktreeManager` — all dependencies are mocked. This is typical for unit tests but means the wiring is only verified at the mock boundary.\n- No test for `--resume` flag combined with parallel mode.\n\n### Architecture concerns\n- The `executeFn` callback doesn't scope the engine to a specific epic's stories, meaning each 